title: For Sale:  Barrett 20" CQ FDE 50 BMG QDL Suppressor Nightforce NXS 8-32x56 NF scope semi auto .50
postcontent:
The Barrett M107A1 .50 BMG semi-automatic rifle is an exceptional firearm! Here are some of the new upgrades: 

* It has the upgraded muzzle brake which gives you less recoil, and enables you to stay on target for faster, more accurate follow up shots. The new 4 chamber muzzlebrake is also able to receive their quick attach suppressor if you ever wanted to silence your 50. (Barrett has said that currently the new muzzlebrake is not available as a separate accessory for the M82A1). 

* It's made of a much stronger, lighter titanium, so even though it's very light it's more durable, and the titanium w/ the upgraded brake keeps recoil down. Also aluminum and steel areas where possible have been thinned for further weight savings without sacrificing the integrity of the design. 

* The mags are much better with a tougher finish, and the mag has sight holes so you can tell exactly how many rounds you have left; our customers that hunt w/ their .50's love that feature, and our troops demand it. 

* The finish on the M107's is much more durable, scratch resistant and rust resistant. 

* It has the thermal cheek guard that allows the shooter to rest their face on the cheek plate and not directly on metal. Also, it's elevated which is ideal because the M107A1 has a really long, elevated mono-rail. 

* It has a lightweight, quick detach bipod with modular feet. 

* It has a monopod as standard equipment instead of having to pay additional and add as an accessory; this is a big help so you do not have to support the weight of the rear of the rifle with your own strength. It also allows you to dial the elevation of where your aiming up or down with the monopod with even more accuracy so even if you don't want to upgrade you may want to ask about adding a monopod. 

*The case it comes with from the factory is an upgrade from a Pelican case to a nicer Storm case. The Storm case is much easier to open and close, and you dont bust your knuckles on it, and the case features padding inside instead of bare plastic. 

Features: 

Suppressor-ready muzzle brake. Lightweight quick-detach bipod with modular feet. Accepts M1913 accessory rails. Thermal cheek guard. Modular hand-grip mounted on M1913 rail. Model:M107A1 Caliber:.50 BMG Operation:Semi-Automatic Rifling Twist:1 turn in 15 (38.1 cm) Magazine Capacity:10 Rounds

title: For Sale:  Chinese Type 56 SKS 7.62x39 C&R
postcontent:
This is a Chinese Type 56 SKS in 7.62x39.  These are early model Chinese that were manufactured on Russian tooling and are all milled.  This one is all matching, including stock.  The bluing has worn above much of the wood line, but there are no corrosion issues or rust.  This is probably due to the rifles being military stored in heavy cosmoline.  This Type 56 has had a thorough cleaning to remove all grease and has been appropriately oiled upon reassembly.  The stock shows some obvious character.  Some people choose to refinish stocks.  I, on the other hand, believe every nick tells a story and do not.  As the new owner, will you leave it with that "been there, done that" battle look?  Or will you refinish in a beautiful blood red?  The bore is pristine and mirror.  Carried a lot, and shot little.  I purchased two of these and have decided to let one go in order to make a little space.  This one has functioned 100% and is a blast to shoot.

Ar15 in .223/5.56 calibre. 
Pistol has 7.5 inch barrel with a krinkov 3 piece muzzle device. Device works absolutely wonderful in sending noise and flash forward away from shooter and nearby shooters. 
10 inch aluminum free float quad rail to cover barrel and 3/4 of the muzzle device while providing a great look, also provides another 3-4 inches of sight radius for the back up sights over many other pistol configurations. 
Has magpul flip back up sights. with extended rail has a decent sight picture with brace extension. 
Has KAK industries Sig brace designed extension tube. Tube has a machined shoulder to prevent the brace from migrating too far forward during firing. Spikes pirate factory filled in lower receiver. 
Quick detach on rail included. Also has quick detach plate on rear of receiver for slings. 
Vortex strike fire Red not included. May trade/sell with rifle for right deal - like optic on trade-
Rifle has seen 400 rounds for break in /sight in. No malfunctions of any kind on testing. Chamber seems to be very forgiving and very accurate. rings steel at 100 yards with garbage ammo while being used as a pistol, also stable for shouldered snap shots. 
Getting burned out on the AR scene and looking to jump ship. If moving to another calibre i have 750 rounds 5.56/.223 ammo to trade for diff calibre ammo.

title: For Sale:  Smith & Wesson 22/32 Heavy Frame Target
postcontent:
Smith & Wesson 22/32 Heavy Frame Target, 6" barrel. Serial number 279xxx, dates this piece in 1917, (per Roy Jinks, S&W Historian) during the "No-Logo" period (1917-1920/21). Uncle Sam took control of the S&W factory to speed up production of the 1917's under US contract, stamping logos was cut to save time and money and not reintroduced until control was given back to S&W.

To be almost 98 years old, the overall condition is very nice. You can see rubs on the cylinder from being shot many times, but thats what this model was made to do. The grips are possibly original (correct medallions) to the gun but have been modified/altered by a prior owner.

Asking $500
